exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Easy
subject: English
stimulus:
The following text is from Hilda Doolittle’s 1916 poem “Storm.”

You crash over the trees,
you crack the live branch—
the branch is white,
the green crushed,
each leaf is rent like split wood.

You burden the trees
with black drops,
you swirl and crash—
you have broken off a weighted leaf
in the wind,
it is hurled out,
whirls up and sinks,
a green stone.
question_stem: Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?

answer_choices.A: To explain the types of weather the speaker is fearful of
answer_choices.B: To detail the speaker’s observations during a weather event
answer_choices.C: To contrast the speaker with a crashing storm
answer_choices.D: To explain the speaker’s dismay about the tree’s destruction

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Easy
subject: English
stimulus:
Text 1

The United States is one of three nations that do not predominantly use the metric system today. Despite efforts in the 1970s, the US was unable to convert its preferred system of measurements to metric. With the world becoming more integrated, it is time for the US to adopt metric as its primary system of measurements. Because the current system in the US does not rely on a consistent numerical factor such as the ten used by the metric system, it is far more prone to miscalculation during unit conversions.

Text 2

While most of the world uses the metric system, the US has the flexibility of keeping its current system while using the metric system on a voluntary basis. Measurements based on everyday things, such as the foot measured in relation to the human body, make sense to people. Still, there are many opportunities to include both systems, such as showing both miles and kilometers on speedometers.
question_stem: Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the underlined claim in Text 1?

answer_choices.A: By dismissing the idea that the US could not contribute to world matters without converting to a metric system
answer_choices.B: By conceding that metric must be used when dealing with international matters
answer_choices.C: By implying that the US should continue using both systems, allowing metric to be used as needed
answer_choices.D: By describing the difficulties that would come with converting entirely to a metric system

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Easy
subject: English
stimulus: Bees are able to distinguish flowers from other objects not only by their colors and odors but also by their electrical field strengths. Field researchers noted that bees were unlikely to land on a flower for about 20 minutes after it had been sprayed with fertilizer. A team of scientists led by Dr. Ellard Hunting explored whether charged particles in fertilizers affected the electrical fields of flowers and whether altered electrical fields changed bee behavior. In an experiment, the scientists sprayed cut flowers with fertilizer, measured the electrical field strength around the flowers, and observed bee behavior around the electrically-manipulated flowers. The team concluded that fertilizer affected the electrical field strength of flowers and caused bees to avoid fertilized flowers.
question_stem: Which finding from the experiment, if true, would most directly support Hunting’s conclusion?

answer_choices.A: There was no noticeable effect on the electric field strength of the flowers sprayed with fertilizer, and bees favored all flowers equally.
answer_choices.B: Fertilized flowers exhibited a noticeable change in their electrical field after fertilizer was applied, and bees tended to be attracted to the electrically manipulated flowers.
answer_choices.C: There was a noticeable effect on the electrical field strength of the flowers sprayed with fertilizer, but bees did not show favor whether the flowers were or were not electrically manipulated.
answer_choices.D: Fertilized flowers exhibited a noticeable change in their electrical field after fertilizer was applied, and bees showed a preference for flowers that were not electrically manipulated.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Easy
subject: English
stimulus: Scientists have discovered a protein present in various species of jellyfish that produces a green fluorescence. Genes containing these green fluorescent proteins (GFPs) can be paired with other genes researchers wish to study and inserted into the genetic codes of animals. GFPs serve to visibly mark the successful implantation of targeted genes. Researchers paired a GFP with a gene that blocks the virus causing feline AIDS and inserted the pair into unfertilized cat eggs. The eggs produced offspring that glowed green, confirming the successful implantation of the viral-blocking gene. A student researching the study asserts that the presence of the gene should not necessarily be correlated with genetic protection against the AIDS virus.
question_stem: Which quotation from a fellow researcher would best support the student’s assertion?

answer_choices.A: “While we can confirm successful implantation of the viral-blocking gene, we still have to do infection studies to verify the gene’s effectiveness.”
answer_choices.B: “The presence of the protection gene in the cats’ lymphoid organs, where the spread of the AIDS virus and subsequent cell death mostly plays out, is encouraging to us.”
answer_choices.C: “We want to see if we can protect the domestic cat against the feline AIDS virus, and if we can expand this research to protect any species against its own corresponding AIDS virus.”
answer_choices.D: “We chose to use cats in this study because cats exhibit more genetic complexity than other animals typically used in AIDS-related research.”

answer_choices.D: The number of Mauritius kestrels showed the most significant increase between 1997 and 2005.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Easy
subject: English
stimulus:
While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes:

  • According to the American Heart Association, seven important factors contribute to cardiovascular health.
  • A team of researchers has proposed adding an eighth factor: sleep.
  • The team’s study found that sleep quality could provide important information about future cardiovascular disease (CVD).
  • A single-factor sleep health score that looked only at sleep duration was predictive of CVD.
  • Sleep health scores can also include multiple factors, such as sleep regularity and daytime sleepiness.
  • Multi-factor sleep health scores were predictive of CVD.
question_stem: The student wants to emphasize a similarity between single-factor and multifactor sleep health scores. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?

answer_choices.A: Sleep health scores can measure different factors, such as sleep duration, sleep regularity, and daytime sleepiness, and can provide information about health.
answer_choices.B: A team of researchers looked at the impact of single-factor and multifactor sleep health scores on cardiovascular health.
answer_choices.C: Single-factor and multifactor sleep health scores measure sleep quality, and both scores are predictive of cardiovascular disease.
answer_choices.D: Multi-factor sleep health scores, unlike single-factor scores, measure multiple factors that include sleep regularity and daytime sleepiness and can provide information about cardiovascular health.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Easy
subject: English
stimulus:
While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes:

  • In geology, the geologic time scale is a type of time division based on the Earth’s rock record.
  • An era has a time span of tens to hundreds of millions of years.
  • The Paleoproterozoic era lasted for 900 million years.
  • The Neoarchean era lasted for 300 million years.
question_stem: The student wants to emphasize the length of the Paleoproterozoic era. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?

answer_choices.A: Covering a span of 900 million years, the Paleoproterozoic era lasted three times as long as the Neoarchean era.
answer_choices.B: The Paleoproterozoic and Neoarchean are eras of different lengths.
answer_choices.C: In geology, time scales are based on the Earth’s rock record, and an era lasts between tens and hundreds of millions of years.
answer_choices.D: An era, such as the Neoarchean era, can last for hundreds of millions of years.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Easy
subject: English
stimulus:
While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes:

  • An optical telescope is an instrument used to observe distant objects.
  • Optical telescopes use lenses, curved mirrors, or a combination.
  • A refractor telescope uses two lenses to focus light into an image.
  • The two lenses are the objective lens and the eyepiece lens.
  • A reflector telescope uses two mirrors to reflect light and form an image.
  • The two mirrors are located at the opposite ends of the telescope.
question_stem: The student wants to contrast refractor and reflector telescopes. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?

answer_choices.A: In refractor telescopes, two lenses are used to focus light into an image, but in reflector telescopes, mirrors are used to reflect light and form an image.
answer_choices.B: A refractor telescope is an instrument that can be used to observe distant objects, but of course, reflector telescopes can be used as well.
answer_choices.C: In refractor and reflector telescopes, different things are used to form images.
answer_choices.D: One of the lenses in a refractor telescope is called the objective lens; the other, in contrast, is called the eyepiece lens.
